04398nam a22004935i 9780226257242DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20152015ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802262572427 a10.7208/97802262572422doi  a(DE-B1597)523335  a(OCoLC)910326344  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aSOC0000002bisacsh00aModes of Uncertainty :bAnthropological Cases /cLimor Samimian-Darash, Paul Rabinow. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b6 line drawings, 5 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER ONE. Uncertainty Makes Us Free: Insurance and Liberal Rationality -- tCHAPTER TWO. The "Cool" Organization Man: Incorporating Uncertainty from Jazz Music into the Business World -- tCHAPTER THREE. The Gaming of Chance: Online Poker Software and the Potentialization of Uncertainty -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Policing Uncertainty: On Suspicious Activity Reporting -- tCHAPTER FIVE. Guantánamo's Catch- 22: The Uncertain Interrogation Subject -- tCHAPTER SIX. Global Humanitarian Interventions: Managing Uncertain Trajectories of Cambodian Mental Health -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. The Malicious and the Uncertain: Biosecurity, Self-Justification, and the Arts of Living -- tCHAPTER EIGHT. What Is a Horizon? Navigating Thresholds in Climate Change Uncertainty -- tCHAPTER NINE. Sentinel Devices: Managing Uncertainty in Species Barrier Zones -- tCHAPTER TEN. Spaces of Uncertainty: Governing Urban Environmental Hazards -- tAFTERWORD. Problematization and Uncertainty -- tNOTES -- tREFERENCES -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aModes of Uncertainty offers groundbreaking ways of thinking about danger, risk, and uncertainty from an analytical and anthropological perspective. Our world, the contributors show, is increasingly populated by forms, practices, and events whose uncertainty cannot be reduced to risk-and thus it is vital to distinguish between the two. Drawing the lines between them, they argue that the study of uncertainty should not focus solely on the appearance of new risks and dangers-which no doubt abound-but also on how uncertainty itself should be defined, and what the implications might be for policy and government. Organizing contributions from various anthropological subfields-including economics, business, security, humanitarianism, health, and environment-Limor Samimian-Darash and Paul Rabinow offer new tools with which to consider uncertainty, its management, and the differing modes of subjectivity appropriate to it. Taking up policies and experiences as objects of research and analysis, the essays here seek a rigorous inquiry into a sound conceptualization of uncertainty in order to better confront contemporary problems. Ultimately, they open the way for a participatory anthropology that asks crucial questions about our contemporary state.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aRabinow, Paul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSamimian-Darash, Limor, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311070422840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226257242423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226257242.jpg  a978-3-11-069043-9  UChP eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-070422-8  UChP eBook-Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles